It's more complicated than that. This is why I keep encouraging some deep thinking on the topic.

Original heavy lifting to Establish Some Things:
https://desuarchive.org/trash/thread/38136544/#38148458
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caniformia

According to current understanding in our world, Caniformia originated in North America in similar fashion to how hominids originated in Africa. Going by that, all canids are "Native Americans." Their diaspora is to the rest of the world from North America, meaning their cradle of civilization may well be Central America, like the Panama & Honduras region.

But, Caniformia originated 50 million years ago, so this vastly precedes the 2 million to 7 million year hominid development coming out of Africa. We're talking about going back to the origins of the ancestors of lemurs when hominids were something of a mouse-like species.

There's enormous room for creative interpretation, as well as creative choices that don't rally require a logical choice. Meaning (as one possible path), raccoons and wolves and foxes could all originate in North America (and the Americas in general) as co-Native Americans. We're exploring a realm here that doesn't exist in our world. We live where only one species dominated everything, humans, with very minor variations in genotype that we see today as races that casually interbreed. Only 35,000 to 50,000 years ago there were three or four closely related hominids that could just barely interbreed with difficulty, and only one of then survived to become us, with traces of genetics of the others.

In this world, we have an unknown number of wolf and fox and dog species (Canidae), plus raccoons (Procyonidae, distant mustilid cousins), plus red pandas (Ailuridae), in a family all by themselves. Within Canidae also exist the raccoon dogs, who are NOT Procyonidae at all (despite their name).

There are two major branches of raccoon dogs, with the main branch living in Asia (and highly invasive in Europe), and a probable sub-species (tanuki) living on the islands of Japan. We're not even sure they can interbreed, although it seems likely. Following the idea of assigning red pandas as "the Chinese," the tanuki fill the equivalent role as "Japanese," which leaves the other branch of raccoon dogs as far Eastern Asians in general, especially Koreans.

The thing is, it isn't really that distinct. There are many species of dogs, foxes & wolves living on every continent with overlapping territories. Arctic foxes could be Siberians, just as much as Finns & Norwegians. And they live in Canada, too.

Consider the wild dog of central-South Asia (basically, India, Afghanistan, Western China, Indonesia) the dhole:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhole

This is a long way of saying that trying to assign these species to places in their world by the nationalities of our world is not a great idea. Or even by our racial divides. There is just too much overlap by the regions they are adapted to. Dhole are just as much native "Chinese" as are red pandas, as are raccoon dogs. We can use a worldmap that is nearly identical to ours, but the country borders will not even be remotely the same. Every "country" has overlapping habitats for different species, so there are multiple species that qualify as "native" based upon ecological niche.

You could generally say that painted dogs are from Africa and dingos are Australians, but you have to allow that other species are also native to those regions/continents. The Americas and Europe are particularly complex because there are so many overlapping species.

Bottom line: each region has multiple species that are "native," not just one. they've all been there for millions of years, not just recent invaders in the last 15,000 or 50,000.

In summary, try to visualize the Earth without countries on it. At least, no countries like we have in our Earth.

Look at the continents. Look at the ecosystems, such as forests and tundra and deserts and open plains. Start looking up species that are interesting to you and look at their habitat range(s). Notice the overlaps, like where raccoons overlap with foxes for one example.

You are free to draw any border and create any country you wish, but those arbitrary lines on the map have little to do with where species occur and are native.

You're on the right track.

In our world, one single species of hominid drove all the others to extinction. Along the way, we picked up some genetic diversity from them as we out-competed & out-bred them.

In drawfren's world, these multiple species never drove each other to extinction. Or, more clearly, the ones who inhabit the modern world are all survivors. I think it's an "of course" fact that some (perhaps many) species were driven to extinction, or never developed into sapient anthros.

Drawfren is still figuring out which species exist. By using Caniformia as the 'super-family,' he has a very rich selection to work through. The reason I liked that idea and went with it is because it allows to divide the entire drawfren alternate Earth into multiple regions with different mixes of species. they are all reasonably related, but very different in environmental and ecological needs. Their direct competition (amongst the survivors) is low enough that they were able to learn to live together, to build civilizations together.

At this point in the world-building, we look at each continent, look at the species that live on them (in our Earth as a template), and start making decisions on which ones grew to fill in and occupy which regions. And, I stress, the overlap of species.

Yes, there will be "countries" almost exclusively of one species, but those will be smallish and unusual compared to other "countries" founded and built by multiple species.

This is not a short path, but the end result will be an established world where many people can jump in and fill out history, details, and culture with stories. A reason why limiting every species to 2 feet tall requires some serious thinking. Completely forgot ... There's a Finnish name for girls that (to me) sounds like a raccoon's name. Tuuri. The double-u is almost a double syllable, but not quite. It's like trying to pronounce both "u"s as a single long sound, with sort of a pause between them. But not quite. For a raccoon, the "r" would be a strong, rolling "rrrr" sound. If you've ever heard a raccoon "chrrrrr" it's a natural sound in their language. It would be similar to saying "two" but drag it out like "tooo" and emphasize the 'rrrrree"

In fact, try to pronounce it with a bit of a silly Scottish accent. When you say "raccoon," get that "oon" sound but finish with an "r" instead of an "n." In your mind, hear a Scotsman say "rrrracooon" and you'll have the rolling "r" down. "Tuurrrie"

As far as all the world-building goes, I'm saying keep an open & and be a bit fluid about the details at this point. Thing's will start to solidify as some of these decisions get made & other factors force their own logic into the world.

You said something about names before, where you were concerned that if you picked one you didn't like later on, you'd be stuck with it. This is a problem every writer/artist/creator has to face. And it applies to the world-building part. Some decisions about the fundamentals of the world & how it works can become limiting, even crippling, factors as they ripple through the logic. Writers face this problem with plot decisions in almost every paragraph.

So, I fall back on the advice I've posted a few times already: spend time meditating and imagining the details of the world, the characters, the possible stories & plots. Watch the logic play out in your mind and make adjustments before decisions become limiting.

For instance, think about the mythology of humans in your world from 3000 and 10,000 years ago. How many humans have crossed over before? At what times? In how many different regions and civilizations? What effect has their appearance had, and their knowledge they brought with them?

What traces of those humans exist today? In the language, in the mythology, any physical traces that might exist but have never been found until now.

I've got about 10 hours of long, hard, mindless physical labor in front of me today. I'll be living a lot of it in your world, tracing the evolution and migration of your species and the march of your civilizations over 10,000 years of your Stone Age before they even discover the Bronze Age and move on to industrialized agriculture. Your Maya/Aztec civ is what Egypt was like in our world.
